# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aws-inspector
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] Cloud computing and storage provide users with the capability to store and process their data in third-party data centers.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] Organizations use the cloud in a variety of service models (e.g., SaaS, PaaS, IaaS) and deployment models (private, public, hybrid, and community).
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] Security concerns associated with cloud computing are typically divided into issues faced by cloud providers and those faced by their customers.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] The responsibility is shared and is often described in a vendor's "shared responsibility model".
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] The provider must secure its infrastructure, while customers must secure their applications, identities, and configuration settings.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] Analyses of large-scale cloud incidents indicate that many breaches result from misconfigurations and long-unremediated exposures rather than solely from zero-day vulnerabilities.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] When an organization stores data or hosts applications on the public cloud, it loses physical access to the hardware.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] As a result, potentially sensitive data may be at risk from insider attacks.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] According to a 2010 Cloud Security Alliance report, insider attacks rank among the top threats in cloud computing.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] Cloud service providers must ensure that thorough background checks are conducted for employees with physical access to data centers.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] To conserve resources and reduce cost, cloud providers often store multiple customers' data on the same server.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] As a result, one user's private data might be viewable by another without proper isolation.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] Providers implement data isolation and logical segregation to mitigate these risks.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] The extensive use of virtualization in cloud infrastructure brings unique security concerns.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] Virtualization introduces an additional layer—the hypervisor—that must be secured and correctly configured.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] A compromise of the hypervisor management system can impact an entire data center.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] Cloud security architecture is effective only if the correct defensive implementations are in place.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] An efficient cloud security architecture should recognize the issues that will arise with security management and follow all the best practices, procedures, and guidelines to ensure a secure cloud environment.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] Security management addresses these issues with security controls.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] These controls protect cloud environments and are put in place to safeguard any weaknesses in the system and reduce the effect of an attack.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] Administrative mechanisms intended to reduce attacks by informing attackers of consequences.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] Controls designed to reduce vulnerabilities and prevent unauthorized access.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] Controls that detect and respond to security events.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] Includes monitoring, SIEM, IDS/IPS, malware detection.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] Controls that reduce the impact of an incident and restore systems.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] Cloud security engineering is characterized by the security layers, plan, design, programming, and best practices that exist inside a cloud security arrangement.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] Cloud security engineering requires the composed and visual model (design and UI) to be characterized by the tasks inside the Cloud.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] This cloud security engineering process includes such things as access to the executives, techniques, and controls to ensure applications and information.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] It also includes ways to deal with and keep up with permeability, consistency, danger stance, and by and large security.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] Processes for imparting security standards into cloud administrations and activities assume an approach that fulfills consistent guidelines and essential foundation security parts.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] Though the idea of cloud computing is not new, organizations are increasingly adopting it because of its flexible scalability, relative trustability, and cost-effectiveness of services.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] However, despite its rapid adoption in some sectors and disciplines, research and statistics indicate that security-related pitfalls remain a major barrier to its full adoption.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] It is generally recommended that information security controls be selected and implemented in proportion to the risks, typically by assessing the threats, vulnerabilities and impacts.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] Cloud security concerns can be grouped in various ways; Gartner identified seven, while the Cloud Security Alliance identified twelve areas of concern.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] Cloud access security brokers (CASBs) are software that sits between cloud users and cloud applications to provide visibility into cloud application usage, data protection and governance to monitor all activity and enforce security policies.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] Any service without a "hardened" environment is considered a "soft" target.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] Virtual servers should be protected just like a physical server against data leakage, malware, and exploited vulnerabilities.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] "Data loss or leakage represents 24.6 % and cloud-related malware 3.4 % of threats causing cloud outages".
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] Every enterprise will have its own identity management system to control access to information and computing resources.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] Cloud providers either integrate the customer's identity management system into their own infrastructure, using federation or SSO technology or a biometric-based identification system, or provide an identity management system of their own.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] Cloud service providers physically secure the IT hardware (servers, routers, cables etc.) against unauthorized access, interference, theft, fire, flood etc., and ensure that essential supplies (such as electricity) are sufficiently robust to minimise the possibility of disruption.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] Various information security concerns relating to personnel involved in cloud services are typically handled through screening, security-awareness training, and role-based access controls.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] Providers ensure that all critical data (credit-card numbers, for example) are masked or encrypted and that only authorised users have access to data in its entirety.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] Moreover, digital identities and credentials must be protected as must any data that the provider collects or produces about customer activity in the cloud.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] Penetration testing is the process of performing offensive security tests on a system, service, or computer network to find security weaknesses in it.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] Since the cloud is a shared environment with other customers or tenants, following penetration-testing rules of engagement step-by-step is a mandatory requirement.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] Scanning and penetration-testing from inside or outside the cloud should be authorised by the cloud provider.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] Scanning the cloud from outside and inside using free or commercial tools is crucial.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] Without a hardened environment, your service is considered a soft target.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] Virtual servers should be hardened just like a physical server against data leakage, malware, and exploited vulnerabilities.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] Privacy legislation often varies by country.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] By having information stored via the cloud it is difficult to determine under which jurisdiction the data falls.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] Trans-border clouds are popular given that the largest companies transcend several countries.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] Legal dilemmas from the ambiguity of the cloud refer to how there is a difference in data-sharing law between and inside organisations.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] Due to the autonomous nature of the cloud, consumers are often given management interfaces to monitor their databases.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] By having controls in one central location and by having the interface be easily accessible for user convenience, there is a possibility that a single actor could gain access to the cloud's management interface; giving them control over much of the system.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] The cloud's use of resource pooling means memory or storage resources may be recycled to another user.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] It is possible for current users to access information left by previous ones.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] Cloud services require internet connectivity and use internet protocols, making them subject to attacks such as man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] Furthermore, heavy reliance on internet connectivity means service disruptions or outages can cut off users entirely.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] As encryption algorithms age, vulnerabilities arise.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] Cloud providers must stay current with encryption standards and transition older systems before they become compromised.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] Some advanced encryption algorithms applied to cloud computing increase the protection of privacy.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] In a practice called crypto-shredding, encryption keys can be deleted when data is no longer used.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] Attribute-based encryption is a form of public-key encryption in which the user's secret key and the ciphertext depend on attributes (e.g., the country the user lives in, or their subscription type).
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] In such systems, access to decryption depends not simply on identity but on attributes.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] Some of the strengths of ABE are that it bypasses the need for explicit key sharing (as in traditional PKI) and identity-based encryption (IBE).
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] However, ABE suffers from key-redistribution complexity: since decryption keys depend on attributes rather than identities, malicious users might leak attribute information, enabling unauthorized access.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] In CP-ABE, the encryptor controls the access policy for the ciphertext.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] The process includes Setup, Encrypt, KeyGen, and Decrypt algorithms; the encryptor defines an access structure that must match a user's attributes before decryption is allowed.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] In KP-ABE, the sender encrypts under a set of attributes, and the user's private key is issued to match a policy describing which ciphertexts they may decrypt.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] KP-ABE shifts access-control responsibility partially to the key-issuer rather than the encryptor.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] While it provides flexibility, the policy disclosure may weaken privacy guarantees.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] Fully Homomorphic Encryption allows arbitrary computation on ciphertext without decryption.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] It is emerging as a high-security option for cloud environments, including voting systems.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] While promising, it remains largely experimental.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] Searchable encryption enables secure search on encrypted data.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] It has symmetric and public-key variants.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] While it supports functionality over encrypted data, it introduces extra attack surfaces, especially when attribute indexing is involved.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] Numerous laws and regulations govern the storage and use of data.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] Similar standards exist in other jurisdictions (e.g., Singapore's Multi-Tier Cloud Security Standard).
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] Similar laws may apply in different legal jurisdictions and may differ markedly from those in the US.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] Cloud service users must often understand the legal and regulatory differences between the jurisdictions.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] For example, data stored by a cloud service provider (CSP) may be located in, say, Singapore and mirrored in the US.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] plans in place to ensure service continuity and data protection.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] In addition to the requirements on customers, data centers used by cloud providers may be subject to additional compliance obligations.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] Using a cloud service provider (CSP) can lead to extra security concerns around data jurisdiction since customer or tenant data may not remain in the same location or provider's cloud.
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] These issues are typically addressed in service-level agreements (SLAs).
[src:aws-inspector/cloud-computing-security] Legal issues may also include records-keeping requirements in the public sector, where agencies must retain and make available electronic records in a specific fashion.
[src:aws-inspector/endpoint-security] The endpoint security space has evolved during the 2010s away from limited antivirus software and into a more advanced, comprehensive defense.
[src:aws-inspector/endpoint-security] This includes next-generation antivirus, threat detection, investigation, and response, device management, data leak protection (DLP), and other considerations to face evolving threats.
[src:aws-inspector/endpoint-security] Endpoint security management is a software approach that helps to identify and manage the users' computer and data access over a corporate network.
[src:aws-inspector/endpoint-security] This allows the network administrator to restrict the use of sensitive data as well as certain website access to specific users, to maintain, and comply with the organization's policies and standards.
[src:aws-inspector/endpoint-security] The components involved in aligning the endpoint security management systems include a virtual private network (VPN) client, an operating system and an updated endpoint agent.
[src:aws-inspector/endpoint-security] Computer devices that are not in compliance with the organization's policy are provisioned with limited access to a virtual LAN.
[src:aws-inspector/endpoint-security] Encrypting data on endpoints, and removable storage devices help to protect against data leaks.
[src:aws-inspector/endpoint-security] Endpoint security systems operate on a client-server model, with the security program controlled by a centrally managed host server pinned with a client program that is installed on all the network drives.
[src:aws-inspector/endpoint-security] There is another model called software as a service (SaaS), where the security programs and the host server are maintained remotely by the merchant.
[src:aws-inspector/endpoint-security] In the payment card industry, the contribution from both the delivery models is that the server program verifies and authenticates the user login credentials and performs a device scan to check if it complies with designated corporate security standards prior to permitting network access.
[src:aws-inspector/endpoint-security] In addition to protecting an organization's endpoints from potential threats, endpoint security allows IT admins to monitor operation functions and data backup strategies.
[src:aws-inspector/endpoint-security] An endpoint protection platform (EPP) is a solution deployed on endpoint devices to prevent file-based malware attacks, detect malicious activity, and provide the investigation and remediation capabilities needed to respond to dynamic security incidents and alerts.
[src:aws-inspector/endpoint-security] Several vendors, like Microsoft Defender, CrowdStrike, and Absolute Security, produce systems converging EPP systems with endpoint detection and response (EDR) platforms – systems focused on threat detection, response, and unified monitoring.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Malware poses serious threats to individuals and businesses on the Internet.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] According to Symantec's 2018 Internet Security Threat Report (ISTR), the number of malware variants increased to 669,947,865 in 2017, which is twice as many malware variants as in 2016.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Cybercrime, which includes malware attacks as well as other crimes committed by computer, was predicted to cost the global economy US$6 trillion in 2021, and is increasing at a rate of 15% per year.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Since 2021, malware has been designed to target computer systems that run critical infrastructure such as the electricity distribution network.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] The defense strategies against malware differ according to its type, but most can be prevented by installing antivirus software or firewalls, applying regular patches, securing networks, creating backups, and isolating infected systems.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Malware can be designed to evade antivirus software detection algorithms.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] The notion of a self-reproducing computer program can be traced back to initial theories about the operation of complex automata.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] John von Neumann showed that in theory a program could reproduce itself.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] This constituted a plausibility result in computability theory.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Fred Cohen experimented with computer viruses and confirmed Neumann's postulate and investigated other properties of malware such as detectability and self-obfuscation using rudimentary encryption.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] His 1987 doctoral dissertation was on the subject of computer viruses.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] The combination of cryptographic technology as part of the payload of the virus, exploiting it for attack purposes was initialized and investigated from the mid-1990s, and includes initial ransomware and evasion ideas.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Before Internet access became widespread, viruses spread on personal computers by infecting executable programs or boot sectors of floppy disks.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] By inserting a copy of itself into the machine code instructions in these programs or boot sectors, a virus causes itself to be run whenever the program is run or the disk is booted.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Early computer viruses were written for the Apple II and Mac, but they became more widespread with the dominance of the IBM PC and MS-DOS.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] The first IBM PC virus in the wild was a boot sector virus dubbed (c)Brain, created in 1986 by the Farooq Alvi brothers in Pakistan.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Malware distributors would trick the user into booting or running from an infected device or medium.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] For example, a virus could make an infected computer add autorunnable code to any USB stick plugged into it.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Anyone who then attached the stick to another computer set to autorun from USB would in turn become infected, and also pass on the infection in the same way.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Older email software would automatically open HTML email containing potentially malicious JavaScript code.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Users may also execute disguised malicious email attachments.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] The *2018 Data Breach Investigations Report* by Verizon, cited by CSO Online, states that emails are the primary method of malware delivery, accounting for 96% of malware delivery around the world.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] The first worms, network-borne infectious programs, originated not on personal computers, but on multitasking Unix systems.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] The first well-known worm was the Morris worm of 1988, which infected SunOS and VAX BSD systems.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Unlike a virus, this worm did not insert itself into other programs.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Instead, it exploited security holes (vulnerabilities) in network server programs and started itself running as a separate process.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] This same behavior is used by today's worms as well.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] With the rise of the Microsoft Windows platform in the 1990s, and the flexible macros of its applications, it became possible to write infectious code in the macro language of Microsoft Word and similar programs.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] These *macro viruses* infect documents and templates rather than applications (executables), but rely on the fact that macros in a Word document are a form of executable code.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Many early infectious programs, including the Morris Worm, the first internet worm, were written as experiments or pranks.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Today, malware is used by both black hat hackers and governments to steal personal, financial, or business information.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Today, any device that plugs into a USB port – even lights, fans, speakers, toys, or peripherals such as a digital microscope – can be used to spread malware.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Devices can be infected during manufacturing or supply if quality control is inadequate.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Since the rise of widespread broadband Internet access, malicious software has more frequently been designed for profit.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Since 2003, the majority of widespread viruses and worms have been designed to take control of users' computers for illicit purposes.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Infected "zombie computers" can be used to send email spam, to host contraband data such as child pornography, or to engage in distributed denial-of-service attacks as a form of extortion.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Malware is used broadly against government or corporate websites to gather sensitive information, or to disrupt their operation in general.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Further, malware can be used against individuals to gain information such as personal identification numbers or details, bank or credit card numbers, and passwords.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Beyond its use in criminal enterprises, malware has also been deployed as a tool for sabotage, often driven by political objectives.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] A notable example is Stuxnet, which was engineered to interfere with specific industrial control systems.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] In other cases, politically motivated malware attacks have targeted entire networks, causing widespread disruption.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] In 2024, a botnet owner was arrested for engaging in a pay-per-install operation for financial gain.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Malware can be classified in numerous ways, and certain malicious programs may fall into two or more categories simultaneously.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Broadly, software can be categorised into three types: (i) goodware; (ii) grayware and (iii) malware.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] A computer virus is software usually hidden within another seemingly harmless program that can produce copies of itself and insert them into other programs or files, and that usually performs a harmful action (such as destroying data).
[src:aws-inspector/malware] They have been likened to biological viruses.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] An example of this is a portable execution infection, a technique, usually used to spread malware, that inserts extra data or executable code into PE files.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] A computer virus is software that embeds itself in some other executable software (including the operating system itself) on the target system without the user's knowledge and consent and when it is run, the virus is spread to other executable files.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] A worm is a stand-alone malware software that *actively* transmits itself over a network to infect other computers and can copy itself without infecting files.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] These definitions lead to the observation that a virus requires the user to run an infected software or operating system for the virus to spread, whereas a worm spreads itself.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Once malicious software is installed on a system, it is essential that it stays concealed, to avoid detection.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Software packages known as *rootkits* allow this concealment, by modifying the host's operating system so that the malware is hidden from the user.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Rootkits can prevent a harmful process from being visible in the system's list of processes, or keep its files from being read.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Some types of harmful software contain routines to evade identification or removal attempts, not merely to hide themselves.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] A backdoor is a broad term for a computer program that allows an attacker persistent unauthorised remote access to a victim's machine often without their knowledge.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] The attacker typically uses another attack (such as a trojan, worm or virus) to bypass authentication mechanisms usually over an unsecured network such as the Internet to install the backdoor application.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] A backdoor can also be a side effect of a software bug in legitimate software that is exploited by an attacker to gain access to a victim's computer or network.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] The idea has often been suggested that computer manufacturers preinstall backdoors on their systems to provide technical support for customers, but this has never been reliably verified.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Backdoors may be installed by Trojan horses, worms, implants, or other methods.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] A Trojan horse misrepresents itself to masquerade as a regular, benign program or utility in order to persuade a victim to install it.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] A Trojan horse usually carries a hidden destructive function that is activated when the application is started.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] The term is derived from the Ancient Greek story of the Trojan horse used to invade the city of Troy by stealth.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Trojan horses are generally spread by some form of social engineering, for example, where a user is duped into executing an email attachment disguised to be unsuspicious, (e.g., a routine form to be filled in), or by drive-by download.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] While Trojan horses and backdoors are not easily detectable by themselves, computers may appear to run slower, emit more heat or fan noise due to heavy processor or network usage, as may occur when cryptomining software is installed.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Cryptominers may limit resource usage or only run during idle times in an attempt to evade detection.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Unlike computer viruses and worms, Trojan horses generally do not attempt to inject themselves into other files or otherwise propagate themselves.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Modern Trojans are often disguised within legitimate-looking applications, making them particularly effective at bypassing basic user awareness and simple antivirus measures.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] In spring 2017, Mac users were hit by the new version of Proton Remote Access Trojan (RAT) trained to extract password data from various sources, such as browser auto-fill data, the Mac-OS keychain, and password vaults.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Droppers are a sub-type of Trojans that solely aim to deliver malware upon the system that they infect with the desire to subvert detection through stealth and a light payload.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] It is important not to confuse a dropper with a loader or stager.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] A loader or stager will merely load an extension of the malware (for example a collection of malicious functions through reflective dynamic link library injection) into memory.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] The purpose is to keep the initial stage light and undetectable.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] A dropper merely downloads further malware to the system.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Ransomware prevents a user from accessing their files until a ransom is paid.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] There are two variations of ransomware, being crypto ransomware and locker ransomware.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Locker ransomware just locks down a computer system without encrypting its contents, whereas crypto ransomware locks down a system and encrypts its contents.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] For example, programs such as CryptoLocker encrypt files securely, and only decrypt them on payment of a substantial sum of money.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Lock-screens, or screen lockers is a type of "cyber police" ransomware that blocks screens on Windows or Android devices with a false accusation in harvesting illegal content, trying to scare the victims into paying up a fee.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Jisut and SLocker impact Android devices more than other lock-screens, with Jisut making up nearly 60 percent of all Android ransomware detections.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Encryption-based ransomware, like the name suggests, is a type of ransomware that encrypts all files on an infected machine.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] These types of malware then display a pop-up ad informing the user that their files have been encrypted and that they must pay (usually in Bitcoin) to recover them.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Some examples of encryption-based ransomware are CryptoLocker and WannaCry.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Some malware is used to generate money by click fraud, making it appear that the computer user has clicked an advertising link on a site, generating a payment from the advertiser.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] It was estimated in 2012 that about 60 to 70% of all active malware used some kind of click fraud, and 22% of all ad-clicks were fraudulent.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Grayware is any unwanted application or file that can worsen the performance of computers and may cause security risks but which there is insufficient consensus or data to classify them as malware.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Types of grayware typically include spyware, adware, fraudulent dialers, joke programs ("jokeware") and remote access tools.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] For example, at one point, Sony BMG compact discs silently installed a rootkit on purchasers' computers with the intention of preventing illicit copying.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Potentially unwanted programs (PUPs) are applications that would be considered unwanted despite often being intentionally downloaded by the user.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] PUPs include spyware, adware, and fraudulent dialers.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Many security products classify unauthorised key generators as PUPs, although they frequently carry true malware in addition to their ostensible purpose.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] (2012) estimated that as much as 55% of key generators could contain malware and that about 36% malicious key generators were not detected by antivirus software.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Some types of adware turn off anti-malware and virus protection; technical remedies are available.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Programs designed to monitor users' web browsing, display unsolicited advertisements, or redirect affiliate marketing revenues are called spyware.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Spyware programs do not spread like viruses; instead they are generally installed by exploiting security holes.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] They can also be hidden and packaged together with unrelated user-installed software.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] The Sony BMG rootkit was intended to prevent illicit copying; but also reported on users' listening habits, and unintentionally created extra security vulnerabilities.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Antivirus software typically uses two techniques to detect malware: (i) static analysis and (ii) dynamic/heuristic analysis.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Static analysis involves studying the software code of a potentially malicious program and producing a signature of that program.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] This information is then used to compare scanned files by an antivirus program.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Because this approach is not useful for malware that has not yet been studied, antivirus software can use dynamic analysis to monitor how the program runs on a computer and block it if it performs unexpected activity.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] The aim of any malware is to conceal itself from detection by users or antivirus software.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Detecting potential malware is difficult for two reasons.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] The first is that it is difficult to determine if software is malicious.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] The second is that malware uses technical measures to make it more difficult to detect it.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] An estimated 33% of malware is not detected by antivirus software.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] The most commonly employed anti-detection technique involves encrypting the malware payload in order to prevent antivirus software from recognizing the signature.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Tools such as crypters come with an encrypted blob of malicious code and a decryption stub.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] The stub decrypts the blob and loads it into memory.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Because antivirus does not typically scan memory and only scans files on the drive, this allows the malware to evade detection.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Advanced malware has the ability to transform itself into different variations, making it less likely to be detected due to the differences in its signatures.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Other common techniques used to evade detection include, from common to uncommon: (1) evasion of analysis and detection by fingerprinting the environment when executed; (2) confusing automated tools' detection methods.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] This allows malware to avoid detection by technologies such as signature-based antivirus software by changing the server used by the malware; (3) timing-based evasion.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] The use of existing binaries to carry out malicious activities is a technique known as LotL, or Living off the Land.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] This reduces the amount of forensic artifacts available to analyze.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Recently these types of attacks have become more frequent with a 432% increase in 2017 and makeup 35% of the attacks in 2018.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Such attacks are not easy to perform but are becoming more prevalent with the help of exploit-kits.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] A vulnerability is a weakness, flaw or software bug in an application, a complete computer, an operating system, or a computer network that is exploited by malware to bypass defences or gain privileges it requires to run.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] For example, TestDisk 6.4 or earlier contained a vulnerability that allowed attackers to inject code into Windows.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] For example, a common method is exploitation of a buffer overrun vulnerability, where software designed to store data in a specified region of memory does not prevent more data than the buffer can accommodate from being supplied.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Malware may provide data that overflows the buffer, with malicious executable code or data after the end; when this payload is accessed it does what the attacker, not the legitimate software, determines.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Malware can exploit recently discovered vulnerabilities before developers have had time to release a suitable patch.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Even when new patches addressing the vulnerability have been released, they may not necessarily be installed immediately, allowing malware to take advantage of systems lacking patches.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Sometimes even applying patches or installing new versions does not automatically uninstall the old versions.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] There are several ways the users can stay informed and protected from security vulnerabilities in software.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Software providers often announce updates that address security issues.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Common vulnerabilities are assigned unique identifiers (CVE IDs) and listed in public databases like the National Vulnerability Database.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Tools like Secunia PSI, free for personal use, can scan a computer for outdated software with known vulnerabilities and attempt to update them.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Firewalls and intrusion prevention systems can monitor the network traffic for suspicious activity that might indicate an attack.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Users and programs can be assigned more privileges than they require, and malware can take advantage of this.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] For example, of 940 Android apps sampled, one third of them asked for more privileges than they required.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Apps targeting the Android platform can be a major source of malware infection but one solution is to use third-party software to detect apps that have been assigned excessive privileges.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Some systems allow all users to make changes to the core components or settings of the system, which is considered over-privileged access today.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] This was the standard operating procedure for early microcomputer and home computer systems, where there was no distinction between an *administrator* or *root*, and a regular user of the system.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] In some systems, non-administrator users are over-privileged by design, in the sense that they are allowed to modify internal structures of the system.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] In some environments, users are over-privileged because they have been inappropriately granted administrator or equivalent status.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] This can be because users tend to demand more privileges than they need, so often end up being assigned unnecessary privileges.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Some systems allow code executed by a user to access all rights of that user, which is known as over-privileged code.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] This was also standard operating procedure for early microcomputer and home computer systems.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Malware, running as over-privileged code, can use this privilege to subvert the system.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Almost all currently popular operating systems, and also many scripting applications allow code too many privileges, usually in the sense that when a user executes code, the system allows that code all rights of that user.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] A credential attack occurs when a user account with administrative privileges is cracked and that account is used to provide malware with appropriate privileges.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Typically, the attack succeeds because the weakest form of account security is used, which is typically a short password that can be cracked using a dictionary or brute force attack.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Using strong passwords and enabling two-factor authentication can reduce this risk.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] With the latter enabled, even if an attacker can crack the password, they cannot use the account without also having the token possessed by the legitimate user of that account.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] It is estimated that approximately 83% of malware infections between January and March 2020 were spread via systems running Windows 10.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] This risk is mitigated by segmenting the networks into different subnetworks and setting up firewalls to block traffic between them.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Anti-malware (sometimes also called antivirus) programs block and remove some or all types of malware.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] For example, Microsoft Security Essentials (for Windows XP, Vista, and Windows 7) and Windows Defender (for Windows 8, 10 and 11) provide real-time protection.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] The Windows Malicious Software Removal Tool removes malicious software from the system.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Additionally, several capable antivirus software programs are available for free download from the Internet (usually restricted to non-commercial use).
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Tests found some free programs to be competitive with commercial ones.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] **Removal:** Anti-malware software programs can be used solely for detection and removal of malware software that has already been installed onto a computer.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] **Sandboxing:** Sandboxing confines applications within a controlled environment, restricting their operations and isolating them from other applications on the host while limiting access to system resources.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Browser sandboxing isolates web processes to prevent malware and exploits, enhancing security.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Any time the operating system accesses a file, the on-access scanner checks if the file is infected or not.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Typically, when an infected file is found, execution is stopped and the file is quarantined to prevent further damage with the intention to prevent irreversible system damage.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Most AVs allow users to override this behaviour.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] This can have a considerable performance impact on the operating system, though the degree of impact is dependent on how many pages it creates in virtual memory.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Sandboxing is a security model that confines applications within a controlled environment, restricting their operations to authorized "safe" actions and isolating them from other applications on the host.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] It also limits access to system resources like memory and the file system to maintain isolation.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Browser sandboxing is a security measure that isolates web browser processes and tabs from the operating system to prevent malicious code from exploiting vulnerabilities.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] It helps protect against malware, zero-day exploits, and unintentional data leaks by trapping potentially harmful code within the sandbox.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] It involves creating separate processes, limiting access to system resources, running web content in isolated processes, monitoring system calls, and memory constraints.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Inter-process communication (IPC) is used for secure communication between processes.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Escaping the sandbox involves targeting vulnerabilities in the sandbox mechanism or the operating system's sandboxing features.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] While sandboxing is not foolproof, it significantly reduces the attack surface of common threats.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Keeping browsers and operating systems updated is crucial to mitigate vulnerabilities.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Website vulnerability scans check the website, detect malware, may note outdated software, and may report known security issues, in order to reduce the risk of the site being compromised.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Structuring a network as a set of smaller networks, and limiting the flow of traffic between them to that known to be legitimate, can hinder the ability of infectious malware to replicate itself across the wider network.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Software-defined networking provides techniques to implement such controls.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] However, malware can still cross the air gap in some situations, not least due to the need to introduce software into the air-gapped network and can damage the availability or integrity of assets thereon.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Stuxnet is an example of malware that is introduced to the target environment via a USB drive, causing damage to processes supported on the environment without the need to exfiltrate data.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] AirHopper, BitWhisper, GSMem and Fansmitter are four techniques introduced by researchers that can leak data from air-gapped computers using electromagnetic, thermal and acoustic emissions.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] Utilizing bibliometric analysis, the study of malware research trends from 2005 to 2015, considering criteria such as impact journals, highly cited articles, research areas, number of publications, keyword frequency, institutions, and authors, revealed an annual growth rate of 34.1%.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] North America led in research output, followed by Asia and Europe.
[src:aws-inspector/malware] China and India were identified as emerging contributors.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] In general, **compliance** means conforming to a rule, such as a specification, policy, standard or law.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] Compliance has traditionally been explained by reference to deterrence theory, according to which punishing a behavior will decrease the violations both by the wrongdoer (specific deterrence) and by others (general deterrence).
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] This view has been supported by economic theory, which has framed punishment in terms of costs and has explained compliance in terms of a cost-benefit equilibrium (Becker 1968).
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] However, psychological research on motivation provides an alternative view: granting rewards (Deci, Koestner and Ryan, 1999) or imposing fines (Gneezy Rustichini 2000) for a certain behavior is a form of extrinsic motivation that weakens intrinsic motivation and ultimately undermines compliance.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] Regulations and accrediting organizations vary among fields, with examples such as PCI-DSS and GLBA in the financial industry, FISMA for U.S. federal agencies, HACCP for the food and beverage industry, and the Joint Commission and HIPAA in healthcare.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] In some cases other compliance frameworks (such as COBIT) or even standards (NIST) inform on how to comply with regulations.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] Some organizations keep compliance data—all data belonging or pertaining to the enterprise or included in the law, which can be used for the purpose of implementing or validating compliance—in a separate store for meeting reporting requirements.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] Compliance software is increasingly being implemented to help companies manage their compliance data more efficiently.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] This store may include calculations, data transfers, and audit trails.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] The ISO also produces international standards such as ISO/IEC 27002 to help organizations meet regulatory compliance with their security management and assurance best practices.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] Some local or international specialized organizations such as the American Society of Mechanical Engineers (ASME) also develop standards and regulation codes.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] They thereby provide a wide range of rules and directives to ensure compliance of the products to safety, security or design standards.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] Regulatory compliance varies not only by industry but often by location.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] The financial, research, and pharmaceutical regulatory structures in one country, for example, may be similar but with particularly different nuances in another country.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] These similarities and differences are often a product "of reactions to the changing objectives and requirements in different countries, industries, and policy contexts".
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] These regulators help to ensure financial institutes meet their promises, that transactional information is well documented, and that competition is fair while protecting consumers.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] Australian organisations seeking to remain compliant with various regulations may turn to AS ISO 19600:2015 (which supersedes AS 3806-2006).
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] This standard helps organisations with compliance management, placing "emphasis on the organisational elements that are required to support compliance" while also recognizing the need for continual improvement.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] In Canada, federal regulation of deposits, insurance, and superannuation is governed by two independent bodies: the OSFI through the Bank Act, and FINTRAC, mandated by the Proceeds of Crime (Money Laundering) and Terrorist Financing Act, 2001 (PCMLTFA).
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] These groups protect consumers, regulate how risk is controlled and managed, and investigate illegal action such as money laundering and terrorist financing.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] On a provincial level, each province maintain individuals laws and agencies.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] Unlike any other major federation, Canada does not have a securities regulatory authority at the federal government level.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] The provincial and territorial regulators work together to coordinate and harmonize regulation of the Canadian capital markets through the Canadian Securities Administrators (CSA).
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] Other key regulators in Canada include the Canadian Food Inspection Agency (CFIA) for food safety, animal health, and plant health; Health Canada for public health; and Environment and Climate Change Canada for environment and sustainable energy.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] For more industry specific guidance, e.g., financial institutions, Canada's E-13 Regulatory Compliance Management provides specific compliance risk management tactics.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] Regulatory compliance in the European Union (EU) is governed by a harmonized legal framework designed to ensure consistency across member states while allowing for national implementation.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] EU compliance regulations cover various industries, including consumer product safety, financial services, environmental protection, and data privacy.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] The General Product Safety Regulation (GPSR) establishes a unified safety framework for consumer products across the EU, requiring manufacturers to conduct risk assessments, maintain traceability documentation, and meet safety compliance standards before placing products on the market.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] The GPSR applies to all consumer products made available in the EU unless covered by sector-specific regulations, such as medical devices or food products.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] The regulation extends to products sold through e-commerce platforms, requiring online marketplaces to ensure that only compliant products are listed.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] Fulfillment service providers are also included as economic operators, making them responsible for product safety compliance in certain cases.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] For business compliance, the EU’s regulatory approach is guided by the New Legislative Framework (NLF) and various sector-specific directives and regulations.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] Businesses must comply with EU product conformity assessments and affix the CE marking to indicate compliance with essential safety and performance standards.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] Financial compliance is enforced through regulations such as the Markets in Financial Instruments Directive (MiFID II) and the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), which set strict requirements for financial transparency, consumer protection, and data security.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] The EU Legislation Compliance framework ensures that organizations operate within the legal boundaries of EU directives, helping public and private entities manage regulatory risks efficiently.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] Companies operating in the EU must stay updated on evolving compliance requirements, as non-compliance can lead to fines, product recalls, or restrictions on market access.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] The financial sector in the Netherlands is heavily regulated.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] The Dutch Central Bank (De Nederlandsche Bank N.V.) is the prudential regulator while the Netherlands Authority for Financial Markets (AFM) is the regulator for behavioral supervision of financial institutions and markets.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] In India, compliance regulation takes place across three strata: Central, State, and Local regulation.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] India veers towards central regulation, especially of financial organizations and foreign funds.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] Compliance regulations vary based on the industry segment in addition to the geographical mix.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] Most regulation comes in the following broad categories: economic regulation, regulation in the public interest, and environmental regulation.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] India has also been characterized by poor compliance - reports suggest that only around 65% of companies are fully compliant to norms.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] The Monetary Authority of Singapore is Singapore's central bank and financial regulatory authority.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] It administers the various statutes pertaining to money, banking, insurance, securities and the financial sector in general, as well as currency issuance.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] There is considerable regulation in the United Kingdom, some of which is derived from European Union legislation.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] Various areas are policed by different bodies, such as the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA), Environment Agency, Scottish Environment Protection Agency, Information Commissioner's Office, Care Quality Commission, and others: see List of regulators in the United Kingdom.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] Important compliance issues for all organizations large and small include the Data Protection Act 2018 and, for the public sector, Freedom of Information Act 2000.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] Corporate scandals and breakdowns such as the Enron case of reputational risk in 2001 have increased calls for stronger compliance and regulations, particularly for publicly listed companies.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] The Office of Foreign Assets Control (OFAC) is an agency of the United States Department of the Treasury under the auspices of the Under Secretary of the Treasury for Terrorism and Financial Intelligence.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] OFAC administers and enforces economic and trade sanctions based on U.S. foreign policy and national security goals against targeted foreign states, organizations, and individuals.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] Compliance in the U.S. generally means compliance with laws and regulations.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] These laws and regulations can have criminal or civil penalties.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] The definition of what constitutes an effective compliance plan has been elusive.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] Most authors, however, continue to cite the guidance provided by the United States Sentencing Commission in Chapter 8 of the Federal Sentencing Guidelines.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] Small Business Administration re-launched Business.gov (later Business.USA.gov and finally SBA.Gov) which provides a single point of access to government services and information that help businesses comply with government regulations.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] Department of Labor, Occupational Health and Safety Administration (OSHA) was created by Congress to assure safe and healthful working conditions for working men and women by setting and enforcing standards and by providing training, outreach, education, and assistance.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] OSHA implements laws and regulations regularly in the following areas, construction, maritime, agriculture, and recordkeeping.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] The United States Department of Transportation also has various laws and regulations requiring that prime contractors when bidding on federally funded projects engage in good faith effort compliance, meaning they must document their outreach to certified disadvantaged business enterprises.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] Data retention is a part of regulatory compliance that is proving to be a challenge in many instances.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] The security that comes from compliance with industry regulations can seem contrary to maintaining user privacy.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] Data retention laws and regulations ask data owners and other service providers to retain extensive records of user activity beyond the time necessary for normal business operations.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] These requirements have been called into question by privacy rights advocates.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] Compliance in this area is becoming very difficult.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] Laws like the CAN-SPAM Act and Fair Credit Reporting Act in the U.S. require that businesses give people the right to be forgotten.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] In other words, they must remove individuals from marketing lists if it is requested, tell them when and why they might share personal information with a third party, or at least ask permission before sharing that data.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] Now, with new laws coming out that demand longer data retention despite the individual’s desires, it can create some real difficulties.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] Money laundering and terrorist financing pose significant threats to the integrity of the financial system and national security.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] To combat these threats, the EU has adopted a risk-based approach to Anti-Money Laundering and Combating the Financing of Terrorism (AML/CFT) that relies on cooperation and coordination between EU and national authorities.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] In this context, risk-based regulation refers to the approach of identifying and assessing potential risks of money laundering and terrorist financing and implementing regulatory measures proportional to those risks.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] However, the shared enforcement powers between EU and national authorities in the implementation and enforcement of AML/CFT regulations can create legal implications and challenges.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] The potential for inconsistent application of AML regulations across different jurisdictions can create regulatory arbitrage and undermine the effectiveness of AML efforts.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] Additionally, a lack of clear and consistent legal frameworks defining the roles and responsibilities of EU and national authorities in AML enforcement can lead to situations where accountability is difficult to establish.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] Corporate Governance Code (formerly the Combined Code) is issued by the Financial Reporting Council (FRC) and "sets standards of good practice in relation to board leadership and effectiveness, remuneration, accountability, and relations with shareholders".
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] All companies with a Premium Listing of equity shares in the U.K. are required under the Listing Rules to report on how they have applied the Combined Code in their annual report and accounts.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] It further demonstrates the relationship that subsists among shareholders, management, and the independent audit teams.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] Financial statements must be prepared using a particular set of rules and regulations hence the rationale behind allowing the companies to apply the provisions of company law, international financial reporting standards (IFRS), as well as the U.K. stock exchange rules as directed by the FCA.
[src:aws-inspector/regulatory-compliance] It is also possible that shareholders may not understand the figures as presented in the various financial statements, hence it is critical that the board should provide notes on accounting policies as well as other explanatory notes to help them understand the report better.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] In computer security, a **vulnerability** is a flaw or weakness in a system's design, implementation, or management that can be exploited by a malicious actor to compromise its security.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] Despite a system administrator's best efforts to achieve complete correctness, virtually all hardware and software contain bugs where the system does not behave as expected.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] If the bug could enable an attacker to compromise the confidentiality, integrity, or availability of system resources, it can be considered a vulnerability.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] Insecure software development practices as well as design factors such as complexity can increase the burden of vulnerabilities.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] Vulnerability management includes identifying systems and prioritizing which are most important, scanning for vulnerabilities, and taking action to secure the system.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] Vulnerability management typically is a combination of remediation, mitigation, and acceptance.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] Vulnerabilities can be scored for severity according to the Common Vulnerability Scoring System (CVSS) and added to vulnerability databases such as the Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures (CVE) database.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] As of April 2026, more than 327,000 vulnerabilities had been recorded in the CVE database.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] A vulnerability is initiated when it is introduced into hardware or software.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] It becomes active and exploitable when the software or hardware containing the vulnerability is running.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] The vulnerability may be discovered by the administrator, vendor, or a third party.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] Publicly disclosing the vulnerability (through a patch or otherwise) is associated with an increased risk of compromise, as attackers can use this knowledge to target existing systems before patches are implemented.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] Vulnerabilities will eventually end when the system is either patched or removed from use.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] Despite a system administrator's best efforts, virtually all hardware and software contain bugs.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] If a bug creates a security risk, it is called a vulnerability.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] Software patches are often released to fix identified vulnerabilities, but zero-days are still liable for exploitation.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] Vulnerabilities vary in their ability to be exploited by malicious actors, and the actual risk is dependent on the nature of the vulnerability as well as the value of the surrounding system.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] Although some vulnerabilities can only be used for denial-of-service attacks, more dangerous ones allow the attacker to perform code injection without the user's awareness.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] Only a minority of vulnerabilities allow for privilege escalation, which is typically necessary for more severe attacks.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] Without a vulnerability, an exploit typically cannot gain access.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] It is also possible for malware to be installed directly, without an exploit, through social engineering or poor physical security such as an unlocked door or exposed port.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] Poor software development practices can affect the likelihood of introducing vulnerabilities to a code base.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] Lack of knowledge or training regarding secure software development, excessive pressure to deliver, or an excessively complex code base can all allow vulnerabilities to be introduced and left unnoticed.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] These factors can also be exacerbated if security is not prioritized by the company culture.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] Inadequate code reviews can also lead to missed bugs, but there are also static code analysis tools that can be used during the code review process to help find some vulnerabilities.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] DevOps, a development workflow that emphasizes automated testing and deployment to speed up the deployment of new features, often requires that many developers be granted access to change configurations, which can lead to deliberate or inadvertent inclusion of vulnerabilities.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] Compartmentalizing dependencies, which is often part of DevOps workflows, can reduce the attack surface by paring down dependencies to only what is necessary.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] If software as a service is used, rather than the organization's own hardware and software, the organization is dependent on the cloud services provider to prevent vulnerabilities.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] Access control vulnerabilities enable an attacker to access a system that is supposed to be restricted to them, or engage in privilege escalation.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] When the system fails to handle and exceptional or unanticipated condition correctly, an attacker can exploit the situation to gain access.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] Configuration vulnerability come into existence when configuration settings cause risks to the system security, leading to such faults as unpatched software or file system permissions that do not sufficiently restrict access.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] A race condition—when timing or other external factors change the outcome and lead to inconsistent or unpredictable results—can cause a vulnerability.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] Deliberate security bugs can be introduced during or after manufacturing and cause the integrated circuit not to behave as expected under certain specific circumstances.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] Testing for security bugs in hardware is quite difficult due to limited time and the complexity of twenty-first century chips, while the globalization of design and manufacturing has increased the opportunity for these bugs to be introduced by malicious actors.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] Although operating system vulnerabilities vary depending on the operating system in use, a common problem is privilege escalation bugs that enable the attacker to gain more access than they should be allowed.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] Open-source operating systems such as Linux and Android have a freely accessible source code and allow anyone to contribute, which could enable the introduction of vulnerabilities.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] However, the same vulnerabilities also occur in proprietary operating systems such as Microsoft Windows and Apple operating systems.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] All reputable vendors of operating systems provide patches regularly.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] Client–server applications are downloaded onto the end user's computers and are typically updated less frequently than web applications.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] Unlike web applications, they interact directly with a user's operating system.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] Because they are inherently less secure than other applications, they are a leading source of data breaches and other security incidents.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] There is little evidence about the effectiveness and cost-effectiveness of different cyberattack prevention measures.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] Although estimating the risk of an attack is not straightforward, the mean time to breach and expected cost can be considered to determine the priority for remediating or mitigating an identified vulnerability and whether it is cost effective to do so.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] Although attention to security can reduce the risk of attack, achieving perfect security for a complex system is impossible, and many security measures have unacceptable cost or usability downsides.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] For example, reducing the complexity and functionality of the system is effective at reducing the attack surface.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] Successful vulnerability management usually involves a combination of remediation (closing a vulnerability), mitigation (increasing the difficulty, and reducing the consequences, of exploits), and accepting some residual risk.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] Often a defense in depth strategy is used for multiple barriers to attack.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] Some organizations scan for only the highest-risk vulnerabilities as this enables prioritization in the context of lacking the resources to fix every vulnerability.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] Increasing expenses is likely to have diminishing returns.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] Remediation fixes vulnerabilities, for example by downloading a software patch.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] Vulnerability scanners are typically unable to detect zero-day vulnerabilities, but are more effective at finding known vulnerabilities based on a database.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] These systems can find some known vulnerabilities and advise fixes, such as a patch.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] However, they have limitations including false positives.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] Vulnerabilities can only be exploited when they are active-the software in which they are embedded is actively running on the system.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] Before the code containing the vulnerability is configured to run on the system, it is considered a carrier.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] Dormant vulnerabilities can run, but are not currently running.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] Software containing dormant and carrier vulnerabilities can sometimes be uninstalled or disabled, removing the risk.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] Active vulnerabilities, if distinguished from the other types, can be prioritized for patching.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] Vulnerability mitigation is measures that do not close the vulnerability, but make it more difficult to exploit or reduce the consequences of an attack.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] Reducing the attack surface, particularly for parts of the system with root (administrator) access, and closing off opportunities for exploits to engage in privilege exploitation is a common strategy for reducing the harm that a cyberattack can cause.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] If a patch for third-party software is unavailable, it may be possible to temporarily disable the software.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] A penetration test attempts to enter the system via an exploit to see if the system is insecure.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] If a penetration test fails, it does not necessarily mean that the system is secure.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] Some penetration tests can be conducted with automated software that tests against existing exploits for known vulnerabilities.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] Other penetration tests are conducted by trained hackers.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] Many companies prefer to contract out this work as it simulates an outsider attack.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] The vulnerability lifecycle begins when vulnerabilities are introduced into hardware or software.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] Detection of vulnerabilities can be by the software vendor, or by a third party.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] In the latter case, it is considered most ethical to immediately disclose the vulnerability to the vendor so it can be fixed.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] Government or intelligence agencies buy vulnerabilities that have not been publicly disclosed and may use them in an attack, stockpile them, or notify the vendor.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] As of 2013, the Five Eyes (United States, United Kingdom, Canada, Australia, and New Zealand) captured the plurality of the market and other significant purchasers included Russia, India, Brazil, Malaysia, Singapore, North Korea, and Iran.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] Organized criminal groups also buy vulnerabilities, although they typically prefer exploit kits.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] Even vulnerabilities that are publicly known or patched are often exploitable for an extended period.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] Security patches can take months to develop, or may never be developed.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] A patch can have negative effects on the functionality of software and users may need to test the patch to confirm functionality and compatibility.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] Larger organizations may fail to identify and patch all dependencies, while smaller enterprises and personal users may not install patches.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] Research suggests that risk of cyberattack increases if the vulnerability is made publicly known or a patch is released.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] Cybercriminals can reverse engineer the patch to find the underlying vulnerability and develop exploits, often faster than users install the patch.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] Vulnerabilities become deprecated when the software or vulnerable versions fall out of use.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] This can take an extended period of time; in particular, industrial software may not be feasible to replace even if the manufacturer stops supporting it.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] A commonly used scale for assessing the severity of vulnerabilities is the open-source specification Common Vulnerability Scoring System (CVSS).
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] CVSS evaluates the possibility to exploit the vulnerability and compromise data confidentiality, availability, and integrity.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] It also considers how the vulnerability could be used and how complex an exploit would need to be.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] The amount of access needed for exploitation and whether it could take place without user interaction are also factored in to the overall score.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] Someone who discovers a vulnerability may disclose it immediately (full disclosure) or wait until a patch has been developed (responsible disclosure, or coordinated disclosure).
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] The former approach is praised for its transparency, but the drawback is that the risk of attack is likely to be increased after disclosure with no patch available.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] Some vendors pay bug bounties to those who report vulnerabilities to them.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] Not all companies respond positively to disclosures, as they can cause legal liability and operational overhead.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] There is no law requiring disclosure of vulnerabilities.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] If a vulnerability is discovered by a third party that does not disclose to the vendor or the public, it is called a zero-day vulnerability, often considered the most dangerous type because fewer defenses exist.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] The most commonly used vulnerability dataset is Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures (CVE), maintained by Mitre Corporation.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] This information is shared into other databases, including the United States' National Vulnerability Database, where each vulnerability is given a risk score using Common Vulnerability Scoring System (CVSS), Common Platform Enumeration (CPE) scheme, and Common Weakness Enumeration.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] CVE and other databases typically do not track vulnerabilities in software as a service products.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] Submitting a CVE is voluntary for companies that discovered a vulnerability.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] The software vendor is usually not legally liable for the cost if a vulnerability is used in an attack, which creates an incentive to make cheaper but less secure software.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-computing] Some companies are covered by laws, such as PCI, HIPAA, and Sarbanes-Oxley, that place legal requirements on vulnerability management.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-scanner] A **vulnerability scanner** is a computer program designed to assess computers, networks or applications for known weaknesses.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-scanner] These scanners are used to discover the weaknesses of a given system.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-scanner] They are used in the identification and detection of vulnerabilities arising from mis-configurations or flawed programming within a network-based asset such as a firewall, router, web server, application server, etc.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-scanner] Modern vulnerability scanners allow for both authenticated and unauthenticated scans.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-scanner] Modern scanners are typically available as SaaS (Software as a Service); provided over the internet and delivered as a web application.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-scanner] The modern vulnerability scanner often has the ability to customize vulnerability reports as well as the installed software, open ports, certificates and other host information that can be queried as part of its workflow.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-scanner] Vulnerability scanners should be able to detect the risks in open-source dependencies.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-scanner] However, since developers will usually re-bundle the OSS, the same code will appear in different dependencies, which will then impact the performance and ability of scanners to detect the vulnerable OSS.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-scanner] The CIS Critical Security Controls for Effective Cyber Defense designates continuous vulnerability scanning as a critical control for effective cyber defense.
[src:aws-inspector/vulnerability-scanner] Part of a server log, showing attempts by a scanner to find the administration page.
